  <h1>Dammam, Khobar and Dhahran Expat Guide 2026</h1>

  <p>The Dammam metropolitan area, encompassing Dammam, Khobar, and Dhahran, is Saudi Arabia's Eastern Province hub and the heartland of the global oil industry. Home to Saudi Aramco's headquarters in Dhahran, this tri-city area attracts thousands of expatriate professionals in energy, engineering, petrochemicals, and related industries. The area offers a unique combination of Aramco compound living, affordable housing, coastal lifestyle on the Persian Gulf coast, and proximity to Bahrain via the King Fahd Causeway, making it one of the most comfortable and financially rewarding expat destinations in Saudi Arabia. With a combined metropolitan population exceeding 2 million, the tri-city area functions as a single urban corridor connected by modern highways.</p>

  <div class="not-prose my-8"><CostOfLivingSimulator client:idle defaultCity="dammam" /></div>

  <h2>Salary Overview</h2>
  <p>Salaries in the Dammam area average SAR 11,200 (~€2,688) per month for expatriates, but the range is wide. Saudi Aramco, the world's most valuable company, sets the standard with comprehensive packages. Entry-level Aramco engineers start at SAR 15,000-20,000 (~€3,600-4,800), mid-level earn SAR 22,000-35,000 (~€5,280-8,400), and senior professionals earn SAR 35,000-55,000 (~€8,400-13,200). Aramco packages include free compound housing, international school allowances, medical care, and annual flights, effectively doubling the value of the base salary. Contractor companies serving Aramco (Jacobs, Worley, McDermott) offer competitive but less comprehensive packages at SAR 12,000-30,000 (~€2,880-7,200). SABIC employees in nearby Jubail earn similar ranges. Healthcare professionals at Johns Hopkins Aramco Healthcare earn well above national averages.</p>
  <p>Beyond the energy sector, salary benchmarks for the Eastern Province include: logistics and supply chain managers at SAR 10,000-18,000 (~€2,400-4,320), IT professionals at SAR 10,000-22,000 (~€2,400-5,280), teachers at international schools at SAR 8,000-14,000 (~€1,920-3,360), retail and hospitality managers at SAR 8,000-15,000 (~€1,920-3,600), and healthcare nurses at SAR 6,000-12,000 (~€1,440-2,880). The Aramco total compensation package, when factoring in free compound housing (valued at SAR 5,000-10,000 (~€1,200-2,400) per month), education allowances of SAR 30,000-50,000 (~€7,200-12,000) per child per year, medical coverage for the entire family, and annual flight tickets, can effectively double or triple the stated base salary. This makes Aramco employment one of the most financially attractive opportunities anywhere in the Gulf.</p>

  <CostOfLivingBreakdown city="Dammam" country="saudi-arabia" />

  <h2>Cost of Living</h2>
  <p>The Eastern Province is the most affordable major metropolitan area in Saudi Arabia. A one-bedroom apartment in Khobar costs SAR 2,000-3,500 (~€480-840), while Dammam is slightly cheaper at SAR 1,800-3,000 (~€432-720). Non-Aramco families renting villas pay SAR 5,000-12,000 (~€1,200-2,880) per month (see our <a href="/saudi-arabia/housing/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">Saudi housing guide</a> for more details). Aramco employees living in company compounds pay nothing for housing. Groceries run SAR 700-1,500 (~€168-360) per month at Tamimi, LuLu, or Panda. The 15% VAT applies to all purchases. For a broader comparison across the Gulf, see our <a href="/guides/best-country-for-expats-gulf/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">best country for expats guide</a>. Dining ranges from SAR 15 (~€4) at local restaurants to SAR 100 (~€24) at Khobar's upscale Corniche venues. The Bahrain causeway (25 km from Khobar) provides weekend access to a more liberal social environment. A single professional can live on SAR 4,500-7,000 (~€1,080-1,680) per month, families on SAR 10,000-18,000 (~€2,400-4,320).</p>
  <p>A practical monthly budget for a single professional in Khobar: rent SAR 2,500 (~€600), utilities SAR 300 (~€72), groceries SAR 800 (~€192), dining out SAR 600 (~€144), transport SAR 400 (~€96), mobile phone SAR 150 (~€36), gym SAR 150 (~€36), and miscellaneous SAR 350 (~€84), totalling approximately SAR 5,250 (~€1,260). This makes the Eastern Province the best value destination in the Gulf for maximizing savings. Coffee at specialty cafes costs SAR 15-25 (~€4-6), cinema tickets at VOX or AMC run SAR 50-70 (~€12-17), and a family dinner at a Khobar Corniche restaurant averages SAR 150-300 (~€36-72). Weekend trips to Bahrain add SAR 200-500 (~€48-120) including the SAR 25 (~€6) causeway toll and dining or entertainment expenses.</p>

  <h2>Neighborhoods and Housing</h2>
  <p>The three cities offer distinct residential characters. Dhahran is dominated by Aramco's residential compound, a self-contained community with American-style amenities including a golf course, pools, schools, recreation centers, commissaries, and shopping facilities, all within a secure gated environment. Khobar is the social hub for non-Aramco expats, with waterfront apartments along the Corniche and family villas in areas like Al Thuqbah, Al Yarmouk, and Al Aqrabiyah. The Khobar Corniche area commands premium rents of SAR 3,000-5,000 (~€720-1,200) for one-bedroom apartments, while inland areas are more affordable. Dammam offers the most affordable housing and is the administrative center with government offices, with one-bedrooms available from SAR 1,800 (~€432). Half Moon Bay, between Dammam and Al Ahsa, provides beachfront weekend getaway options.</p>
  <p>For families, the compound lifestyle in the Eastern Province is particularly well-suited to settling in quickly. Aramco's residential camps in Dhahran, Ras Tanura, and Abqaiq provide ready-made communities where children can play outdoors safely, and social connections form naturally through sports leagues, book clubs, and community events. Non-Aramco compound options in Khobar include the SASREF compound and various smaller gated communities. Outside of compounds, newer residential developments along Prince Turki Road in Khobar offer modern apartment buildings with facilities including swimming pools, gyms, and children's play areas. When selecting housing, proximity to your employer is the primary consideration, as commuting between the three cities during peak hours can add 30-45 minutes to your journey despite relatively short distances.</p>

  <h2>Commuting and Transportation</h2>
  <p>The three cities are connected by well-maintained highways, and the tri-city area is compact enough that most destinations are reachable within 30-40 minutes. The Khobar-Dammam Highway and the Dhahran-Jubail Highway are the main arteries. Traffic is generally lighter than Riyadh or Jeddah, though the King Fahd Causeway approach road to Bahrain becomes congested on Thursday evenings and Friday mornings as residents head for the weekend. Aramco provides shuttle buses between its residential compounds and work locations, eliminating the need for many employees to drive. For non-Aramco expats, car ownership is essential (see our <a href="/guides/driving-licence/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">driving licence guide</a> for the Saudi conversion process), and fuel at SAR 2.18 (~€0.52) per liter making driving very affordable. Ride-hailing via Uber and Careem is available throughout the metro area. There is no metro system in the Eastern Province, and public bus services are limited. Parking is free almost everywhere, including at malls and offices. The King Fahd International Airport (KFIA) in Dammam connects to regional and international destinations, with direct flights to Dubai (1 hour), Bahrain (20 minutes by car via the causeway), Riyadh (1 hour), and major international cities.</p>

  <h2>Working in the Eastern Province</h2>
  <p>Employment is heavily concentrated in energy and petrochemicals. Saudi Aramco and its network of contractors are the largest employers by far. SABIC operates major facilities in Jubail Industrial City (90 km north), one of the world's largest industrial complexes. Ma'aden (mining) and various industrial firms provide additional opportunities in the minerals and metals sector. King Fahd University of Petroleum and Minerals (KFUPM) employs academic staff and researchers across engineering, science, and business disciplines. Healthcare employment through Johns Hopkins Aramco Healthcare (JHAH) and government hospitals including King Fahd Hospital and Dammam Medical Complex is significant, with JHAH actively recruiting international physicians, nurses, and allied health professionals. The work week follows the standard Saudi schedule of Sunday to Thursday, though Aramco operates some facilities on different shift patterns including rotational schedules for field operations.</p>
  <p>The Eastern Province also supports a growing logistics sector centered on King Abdulaziz Port in Dammam and the King Fahd Industrial Port in Jubail. These facilities create demand for logistics, freight forwarding, and supply chain professionals. The retail and hospitality sectors have expanded with new mall developments in Khobar and Dammam, including the Al Rashid Mall and Dhahran Mall. Networking opportunities exist through the Eastern Province Chamber of Commerce, professional associations, and the numerous industry conferences held at the Dhahran Expo center.</p>

  <h2>Schools and Education</h2>
  <p>The Eastern Province has a strong selection of <a href="/saudi-arabia/education/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">international schools</a>, many with close ties to the Aramco community. Dhahran British Grammar School, one of the oldest British curriculum schools in Saudi Arabia, is well-regarded for academic results. International Schools Group (ISG) offers both American and British curricula across its Dhahran and Jubail campuses. Dhahran Ahliyya Schools provides a bilingual Arabic-English education. For more affordable options, Indian CBSE schools including International Indian School Al Khobar and Al Hussan International School charge SAR 8,000-15,000 (~€1,920-3,600) per year. Aramco operates its own school system for dependents of employees, offering American-curriculum education at no cost to families. Premium international school fees in the area range from SAR 25,000-55,000 (~€6,000-13,200) per year. For higher education, KFUPM in Dhahran is one of the top-ranked universities in the Arab world for engineering and petroleum studies.</p>

  <h2>Healthcare Facilities</h2>
  <p>Healthcare in the Eastern Province is anchored by Johns Hopkins Aramco Healthcare (JHAH), which provides comprehensive medical services to Aramco employees and their families at facilities in Dhahran, Al Hasa, and Ras Tanura. JHAH is affiliated with Johns Hopkins Medicine and maintains international accreditation standards. For non-Aramco expats, Saad Specialist Hospital in Khobar is one of the largest private hospitals in the region, offering a full range of specialties including oncology, cardiology, and orthopedics. Mouwasat Medical Group operates hospitals in Dammam and Jubail. King Fahd Hospital of the University and Dammam Central Hospital serve as major public healthcare facilities. GP consultations at private clinics cost SAR 100-200 (~€24-48), and specialist visits run SAR 200-400 (~€48-96). All employers must provide CCHI-approved <a href="/saudi-arabia/healthcare/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">health insurance</a>.</p>

  <h2>Lifestyle and Recreation</h2>
  <p>The Eastern Province offers a more relaxed lifestyle than Riyadh. Khobar Corniche is the social hub with restaurants, cafes, and sea views stretching along the waterfront promenade. Half Moon Beach, a crescent-shaped bay south of Khobar, is popular for camping, jet-skiing, and barbecues on weekends. The King Fahd Causeway connects to Bahrain (30-minute drive), providing access to restaurants, hotels, cinemas, and entertainment that are a staple of Eastern Province social life. Weekend trips to Bahrain are one of the defining features of expat life in the area. Ithra (King Abdulaziz Center for World Culture) in Dhahran is a world-class cultural center with museums, a library, a cinema, and event spaces, offering programming ranging from children's workshops to international exhibitions. The area has a strong community feel, with sports leagues (softball, rugby, tennis, golf at the Aramco course), social clubs, and expat associations well-established after decades of international presence. The Aramco Annuitants reunion and various community events create a sense of continuity and belonging. Dining options have expanded notably, with the Khobar Corniche area now home to international restaurants, specialty coffee shops, and dessert cafes. For outdoor enthusiasts, weekend camping in the desert, diving at the Jubail marine sanctuary, and fishing trips in the Persian Gulf are popular activities.</p>

